{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"19685c85-9cb4-4789-a040-22240b770b58","content":"The best approach is `dotnet-trace` with the CPU profiling preset:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app/).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a [sidecar or ephemeral container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-an-ephemeral-container) with `kubectl debug`.\n- For lower overhead in production, consider `dotnet-trace collect --profile cpu-sampling --buffersize 256` to limit memory use.\n- To copy the trace out: `kubectl cp <pod>:<path-to-nettrace> ./trace.nettrace`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f91c9d0f-31ed-4029-8060-cfbfa6cd8bb3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":335,"requestId":"C3DA:23AB21:1E2B2F2:21CAE34:6A07C33F"},"id":"ba003975-3498-436d-8ab0-e2a7bc057f89","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:07:20.446Z","parentId":"0f0b0bb9-4903-40e7-be40-7c77691f8840"}
